    Overview¶

    This notebook covers the essentials of prompt engineering, including some best practices.

    Learn more about prompt design in the official documentation.

    In this notebook, you learn best practices around prompt engineering -- how to design prompts to improve the quality of your responses.

    This notebook covers the following best practices for prompt engineering:

    • Be concise
    • Be specific and well-defined
    • Ask one task at a time
    • Turn generative tasks into classification tasks
    • Improve response quality by including examples

    Prompt engineering best practices¶

    Prompt engineering is all about how to design your prompts so that the response is what you were indeed hoping to see.

    The idea of using "unfancy" prompts is to minimize the noise in your prompt to reduce the possibility of the LLM misinterpreting the intent of the prompt. Below are a few guidelines on how to engineer "unfancy" prompts.

    In this section, you'll cover the following best practices when engineering prompts:

    • Be concise
    • Be specific, and well-defined
    • Ask one task at a time
    • Improve response quality by including examples
    • Turn generative tasks to classification tasks to improve safety

    Be concise¶

    Be specific, and well-defined¶

    Suppose that you want to brainstorm creative ways to describe Earth.

    🛑 The prompt below might be a bit too generic (which is certainly OK if you'd like to ask a generic question!)

    [14]:
     
    prompt = "Tell me about Earth"
    ​
    response = client.models.generate_content(model=MODEL_ID, contents=prompt)
    display(Markdown(response.text))

    Earth, our home planet, is a truly remarkable and unique celestial body. It's the third planet from the Sun and the only known place in the universe to harbor life.

    Here's a breakdown of some key facts and characteristics about Earth:

    1. Basic Identity:

      • Name: Earth (from Old English "eorðe," meaning "ground" or "land").
      • Type: Terrestrial (rocky) planet.
      • Nickname: "The Blue Planet" (due to its abundant water), "The Water Planet."

    2. Location in the Solar System:

      • Orbit: Third planet from the Sun, orbiting at an average distance of about 150 million kilometers (93 million miles).
      • Habitable Zone: Located within the Sun's "habitable zone" or "Goldilocks zone," where conditions are just right for liquid water to exist on the surface.

    3. Physical Characteristics:

      • Shape: An oblate spheroid, meaning it's slightly flattened at the poles and bulges at the equator due to its rotation.
      • Size: Fifth-largest planet in the Solar System by diameter (approx. 12,742 km or 7,918 miles).
      • Mass: Approximately 5.97 x 10^24 kg.
      • Density: The densest planet in the Solar System.

    4. Internal Structure:

      • Crust: The outermost solid layer, relatively thin and composed of continental and oceanic plates.
      • Mantle: A thick, semi-solid layer of silicate rock below the crust, where convection currents drive plate tectonics.
      • Outer Core: A liquid layer of iron and nickel, responsible for generating Earth's magnetic field.
      • Inner Core: A solid sphere of iron and nickel at the very center, intensely hot and under immense pressure.

    5. Atmosphere:

      • Composition: Primarily Nitrogen (78%), Oxygen (21%), with trace amounts of Argon, Carbon Dioxide, water vapor, and other gases.
      • Layers: Divided into several layers: troposphere (where weather occurs), stratosphere (contains the ozone layer), mesosphere, thermosphere, and exosphere.
      • Function: Provides breathable air, protects from harmful UV radiation (ozone layer), regulates temperature through the greenhouse effect, and burns up most incoming meteoroids.

    6. Water:

      • Abundance: About 71% of Earth's surface is covered by water, mostly in oceans.
      • Forms: Exists in all three states: liquid (oceans, lakes, rivers), solid (ice caps, glaciers), and gas (water vapor in the atmosphere).
      • Importance: Liquid water is crucial for the existence of life as we know it.

    7. Life:

      • Biodiversity: Home to an incredible diversity of life forms, from microscopic bacteria to giant whales, living in a vast array of ecosystems.
      • Evolution: Life on Earth has evolved over billions of years, adapting to various environments.

    8. Geological Activity:

      • Plate Tectonics: Earth's crust is broken into several large plates that are constantly moving, causing earthquakes, volcanic activity, and the formation of mountains and ocean trenches.
      • Weathering & Erosion: Continuous processes that shape the Earth's surface.

    9. Movement:

      • Rotation: Rotates on its axis approximately every 24 hours, causing day and night.
      • Orbit: Orbits the Sun every 365.25 days (one year).
      • Axial Tilt: Tilted at approximately 23.5 degrees relative to its orbital plane, which is responsible for the seasons.

    10. Magnetic Field (Magnetosphere):

      • Generated by the liquid outer core, it acts as a protective shield, deflecting harmful charged particles from the Sun (solar wind) and cosmic rays. This protection is vital for life on Earth.

    In summary, Earth is a dynamic, living planet, a delicate balance of physical processes, chemical cycles, and biological interactions that have made it a unique oasis in the cosmos. Its remarkable features, especially the presence of liquid water and a protective atmosphere, have allowed life to flourish and evolve into the incredible biodiversity we see today.

    ✅ Recommended. The prompt below is specific and well-defined.

    [15]:
     
    prompt = "Generate a list of ways that makes Earth unique compared to other planets"
    ​
    response = client.models.generate_content(model=MODEL_ID, contents=prompt)
    display(Markdown(response.text))

    Earth stands out in many ways when compared to other planets, both within our solar system and the thousands of exoplanets discovered so far. Here are some of its most unique characteristics:

    1. Abundant, Stable Liquid Water on its Surface: While water ice is common and subsurface oceans are suspected on some moons (like Europa or Enceladus), Earth is the only known planet with vast quantities of stable liquid water on its surface. This is a primary ingredient for life as we know it.

    2. A Global Biosphere and Diverse Life: Earth is the only planet known to harbor life, from simple single-celled organisms to incredibly complex, multicellular, and intelligent beings. The sheer biodiversity is unparalleled.

    3. Oxygen-Rich Atmosphere: Our atmosphere is about 21% oxygen, a direct product of photosynthetic life. This high oxygen content is crucial for the existence of complex animal life, and it's virtually unique among planetary atmospheres in our solar system (others are mostly CO2, H2, He, or N2).

    4. Active Plate Tectonics: Earth is the only known body in our solar system with active, global plate tectonics. This process constantly recycles the planet's crust, drives volcanism, creates mountain ranges, and plays a crucial role in regulating Earth's climate over geological timescales by influencing the carbon cycle.

    5. A Large, Stabilizing Moon: Earth's Moon is unusually large relative to its parent planet. Its gravitational pull stabilizes Earth's axial tilt, preventing dramatic wobbles that could lead to extreme climate shifts and making conditions more stable for the evolution of life.

    6. A Robust Global Magnetic Field (Magnetosphere): Earth's molten iron core generates a powerful magnetic field that extends far into space. This magnetosphere deflects harmful solar wind and cosmic radiation, preventing the stripping away of our atmosphere and protecting surface life. While other planets have magnetic fields, Earth's is particularly strong and effective in this role.

    7. Complex Water Cycle: Earth has a unique and intricate water cycle involving evaporation, condensation, precipitation (rain, snow, ice), and surface/subsurface flow. This continuously redistributes water across the planet.

    8. Temperate "Goldilocks Zone" Location: Earth orbits within the Sun's habitable zone (or "Goldilocks zone"), where temperatures are "just right" for liquid water to exist on the surface. It's not too hot like Venus, nor too cold like Mars.

    9. Vast and Deep Oceans: Covering about 71% of its surface, Earth's oceans are incredibly deep and play a vital role in regulating climate, distributing heat, and supporting a massive portion of Earth's biodiversity.

    10. A Stable and Long-Lived Climate: While Earth's climate has changed significantly over geological time, it has remained remarkably stable enough for life to evolve and diversify over billions of years, thanks to feedback loops involving oceans, atmosphere, and plate tectonics.

    These interconnected factors make Earth an extraordinary planet, a true oasis for life in the vastness of the cosmos.

    Ask one task at a time¶

    🛑 Not recommended. The prompt below has two parts to the question that could be asked separately.

    [16]:
     
    prompt = "What's the best method of boiling water and why is the sky blue?"
    ​
    response = client.models.generate_content(model=MODEL_ID, contents=prompt)
    display(Markdown(response.text))

    Let's tackle both of your excellent questions!

    What's the best method of boiling water?¶

    "Best" can depend on your priorities (speed, energy efficiency, volume, portability, safety), but generally, for everyday home use, the electric kettle is often considered the best.

    Here's a breakdown of common methods and their pros/cons:

    1. Electric Kettle (The Winner for Most Situations)

      • Pros:
        • Speed: Extremely fast. The heating element is immersed directly in the water, transferring heat very efficiently.
        • Energy Efficiency: Highly efficient because almost all the energy goes directly into heating the water, with minimal heat loss to the surrounding air. Many automatically shut off when boiling, preventing wasted energy.
        • Convenience: Simple to use, portable (as long as there's an outlet), and safer than an open flame.
        • No Stove Needed: Frees up stovetop space.
      • Cons: Requires electricity, generally for smaller to medium volumes (though large kettles exist).

    2. Stovetop Pot with a Lid

      • Pros:
        • Versatility: Can handle any volume of water, from a small cup to a large stockpot.
        • No Special Appliance: Just a pot and a stove.
        • Good for Large Volumes: If you need to boil several gallons, this is usually the go-to.
      • Cons:
        • Slower: Especially on electric coil stoves, but even gas can be slower than an electric kettle due to heat loss.
        • Less Energy Efficient: Heat can escape from the sides of the pot and into the kitchen air.
        • Requires Monitoring: You need to watch it to prevent boil-overs.
      • Tip: Always use a lid! This traps steam and heat, significantly speeding up the boiling process and saving energy.

    3. Microwave

      • Pros: Convenient for very small amounts (e.g., a single cup for tea).
      • Cons:
        • Superheating Risk: Water can heat past its boiling point without actually bubbling (superheated). When disturbed (like adding a tea bag), it can violently erupt, causing severe burns. This is a significant safety concern.
        • Uneven Heating: Can result in hot spots and cold spots.
        • Less Efficient: For larger volumes, it's generally slower and less efficient than a kettle or stovetop.

    Conclusion for Boiling Water: For speed, energy efficiency, and convenience in a typical home setting, the electric kettle is the best method. For large volumes or situations where you don't have an electric kettle, a stovetop pot with a lid is the next best option. Avoid the microwave for boiling unless you are extremely cautious about superheating risks and only need a very small amount.

    Why is the sky blue?¶

    The sky is blue because of a phenomenon called Rayleigh Scattering.

    Here's how it works:

    1. Sunlight is White Light: Sunlight, which appears white to us, is actually made up of all the colors of the rainbow (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet). Each color has a different wavelength, with red having the longest and violet the shortest.

    2. Earth's Atmosphere: Our atmosphere is composed of tiny gas molecules (primarily nitrogen and oxygen). These molecules are much smaller than the wavelengths of visible light.

    3. Scattering of Light: When sunlight enters the atmosphere, it collides with these tiny gas molecules. The molecules "scatter" the light in all directions.

    4. Wavelength Matters: Rayleigh scattering states that shorter wavelengths of light (like blue and violet) are scattered much more effectively and intensely than longer wavelengths (like red and yellow). Imagine it like this: the small atmospheric particles are more effective at bouncing around the smaller, quicker blue waves than the longer, lazier red waves.

    5. What We See: As sunlight travels through the atmosphere, the blue and violet light gets scattered in every direction. When you look up at the sky, you are seeing this scattered blue light coming from all around you. Our eyes are more sensitive to blue than violet, and there's also slightly more blue light in the sun's spectrum that reaches us, so the sky appears predominantly blue.

    6. Why Not Violet? While violet light is scattered even more than blue, our eyes are less sensitive to violet, and there's simply less violet light present in the sun's spectrum to begin with compared to blue.

    7. Sunrise/Sunset: At sunrise and sunset, the sun's light has to travel through much more of the Earth's atmosphere to reach your eyes. By the time it reaches you, most of the blue and violet light has been scattered away, leaving the longer-wavelength colors like red, orange, and yellow to pass directly through, which is why we see those beautiful fiery hues.

    ✅ Recommended. The prompts below asks one task a time.

    [17]:
     
    prompt = "What's the best method of boiling water?"
    ​
    response = client.models.generate_content(model=MODEL_ID, contents=prompt)
    display(Markdown(response.text))

    The "best" method for boiling water really depends on your priorities: speed, energy efficiency, safety, and available equipment.

    Here's a breakdown of the most common methods and their pros and cons:

    1. Electric Kettle (Generally the Best All-Around)¶

    • Pros:
      • Speed: Often the fastest method, especially for moderate amounts (1-2 liters).
      • Energy Efficiency: Very efficient because the heating element is directly immersed in the water, and they usually have auto-shutoff features, preventing over-boiling.
      • Convenience: Simple to use, portable (within reach of an outlet), and usually has an auto-shutoff.
      • Safety: No open flame, and the auto-shutoff prevents hazards if you forget it.
    • Cons:
      • Requires an electrical outlet.
      • Another appliance to store.
      • Capacity is usually limited.

    Best for: Most everyday uses, making tea/coffee, small cooking tasks, general convenience.

    2. Induction Stovetop (Extremely Fast & Efficient, if you have one)¶

    • Pros:
      • Speed: Can be as fast or even faster than an electric kettle for larger quantities, as it heats the pot directly and very quickly.
      • Energy Efficiency: Highly efficient because the magnetic field heats the pot directly, with very little energy wasted to the air.
      • Safety: The cooktop itself doesn't get hot (only the pot), reducing burn risk.
    • Cons:
      • Requires induction-compatible cookware (magnetic bottom).
      • Induction cooktops are more expensive to install than gas or traditional electric.

    Best for: Rapid boiling of larger quantities, if you have an induction setup and compatible pots.

    3. Gas Stovetop (Fast & Responsive)¶

    • Pros:
      • Speed: Heats up quickly due to direct flame contact with the pot.
      • Responsiveness: Easy to adjust heat instantly.
      • Common: Most homes have one.
    • Cons:
      • Energy Efficiency: Less efficient than electric kettles or induction because a significant amount of heat escapes around the sides of the pot.
      • Safety: Open flame, can be a fire hazard if unsupervised.
      • Air Quality: Releases small amounts of combustion byproducts into the air.

    Best for: General cooking, boiling larger quantities where an electric kettle might be too small, if you don't have induction.

    4. Traditional Electric Coil/Radiant Stovetop (Slower & Less Efficient)¶

    • Pros:
      • Common: Widely available.
    • Cons:
      • Speed: Slower because the element heats up, then the element heats the pot.
      • Energy Efficiency: Less efficient than gas or induction due to heat loss from the element to the air.
      • Safety: The element stays hot for a long time after being turned off, posing a burn risk.

    Best for: Boiling water if it's the only stovetop option available.

    5. Microwave (Not Recommended for Boiling)¶

    • Pros:
      • Convenient for very small amounts (e.g., a single cup of water).
      • No extra appliance on the counter.
    • Cons:
      • Speed: Generally slower than other methods for boiling, especially for larger quantities.
      • Uneven Heating: Can create "hot spots" and lead to superheated water, which is extremely dangerous. Superheated water can violently erupt when disturbed (e.g., by adding a tea bag or moving the cup), causing severe burns.
      • No visual cue of boiling.
      • Not very energy efficient for boiling.

    Best for: Avoid boiling water in the microwave if possible. If you must, use a non-sealed, microwave-safe container (not glass), add a non-metallic object (like a wooden stir stick or ceramic mug) to provide a nucleation site for bubbles, and heat in short bursts, stirring in between.

    Tips for Boiling Water More Efficiently (Regardless of Method):¶

    1. Use a Lid: This traps steam and heat, significantly speeding up the boiling process and saving energy.
    2. Only Boil What You Need: Don't fill a 2-liter kettle to boil a single cup of water.
    3. Start with Hot Tap Water (if safe): If your tap water gets hot quickly and is safe to drink, using hot water from the tap can shave a minute or two off the boiling time. (Note: Some experts advise against drinking hot tap water due to potential for dissolved contaminants from pipes, so use discretion).
    4. Descale Your Kettle/Pots: Limescale buildup acts as an insulator, making kettles and pots less efficient. Regularly descale with vinegar or citric acid.
    5. Use a Wide-Bottomed Pot (for stovetop): A wider base allows for more direct contact with the heat source, improving efficiency.

    In summary, for most people and most uses, the electric kettle is the clear winner for speed, efficiency, and convenience. If you have an induction stovetop and suitable cookware, that's an equally excellent choice.

    [18]:
     
    prompt = "Why is the sky blue?"
    ​
    response = client.models.generate_content(model=MODEL_ID, contents=prompt)
    display(Markdown(response.text))

    The sky is blue primarily due to a phenomenon called Rayleigh Scattering. Here's a breakdown:

    1. Sunlight is White Light: Sunlight, when it reaches Earth, appears white to us, but it's actually made up of all the colors of the rainbow (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet). Each color has a different wavelength – red has the longest wavelength, and violet/blue have the shortest.

    2. Earth's Atmosphere: Our atmosphere is composed mainly of tiny gas molecules (about 78% nitrogen and 21% oxygen), along with some argon, carbon dioxide, water vapor, and tiny dust particles. These molecules are much smaller than the wavelengths of visible light.

    3. Rayleigh Scattering: When sunlight enters the atmosphere, it collides with these tiny gas molecules.

      • Short wavelengths scatter more: Because blue and violet light have very short wavelengths, they are scattered much more effectively and in all directions by the tiny nitrogen and oxygen molecules. Think of it like trying to navigate a large wave (red light) through a small group of pebbles versus a small ripple (blue light) – the ripple gets deflected more easily.
      • Long wavelengths pass through: Longer wavelengths, like red, orange, and yellow light, are not scattered as much and tend to travel more directly through the atmosphere.

    4. Why We See Blue (and not Violet):

      • While violet light is scattered even more than blue light, there are two main reasons why the sky appears blue to us:
        • Sun's Spectrum: The sun actually emits slightly more blue light than violet light.
        • Our Eyes' Sensitivity: Our eyes are more sensitive to blue light than to violet light. So, even though violet is present and scattered, our perception favors blue.

    5. The Result: As we look up at the sky, the blue light that has been scattered in all directions reaches our eyes from every part of the atmosphere, making the sky appear blue. The other colors (red, orange, yellow) largely pass through the atmosphere and reach us directly from the sun, which is why the sun itself appears yellowish-white in the sky.

    What about other times, like sunsets?

    When the sun is low on the horizon (during sunrise or sunset), its light has to travel through a much greater amount of atmosphere to reach our eyes. By the time it reaches us, nearly all the blue and violet light has been scattered away, leaving mostly the longer-wavelength red, orange, and yellow light to come directly through. This is why sunrises and sunsets often look fiery red, orange, and pink.

    ### Watch out for hallucinations
    xxxxxxxxxx

    Although LLMs have been trained on a large amount of data, they can generate text containing statements not grounded in truth or reality; these responses from the LLM are often referred to as "hallucinations" due to their limited memorization capabilities. Note that simply prompting the LLM to provide a citation isn't a fix to this problem, as there are instances of LLMs providing false or inaccurate citations. Dealing with hallucinations is a fundamental challenge of LLMs and an ongoing research area, so it is important to be cognizant that LLMs may seem to give you confident, correct-sounding statements that are in fact incorrect.

    Note that if you intend to use LLMs for the creative use cases, hallucinating could actually be quite useful.

    Try the prompt like the one below repeatedly. We set the temperature to 1.0 so that it takes more risks in its choices. It's possible that it may provide an inaccurate, but confident answer.

    [19]:
     
    generation_config = GenerateContentConfig(temperature=1.0)
    ​
    prompt = "What day is it today?"
    ​
    response = client.models.generate_content(model=MODEL_ID, contents=prompt)
    display(Markdown(response.text))

    Today is Sunday.

    xxxxxxxxxx

    Since LLMs do not have access to real-time information without further integrations, you may have noticed it hallucinates what day it is today in some of the outputs.

    Using system instructions to guardrail the model from irrelevant responses¶

    How can we attempt to reduce the chances of irrelevant responses and hallucinations?

    One way is to provide the LLM with system instructions.

    Let's see how system instructions works and how you can use them to reduce hallucinations or irrelevant questions for a travel chatbot.

    Suppose we ask a simple question about one of Italy's most famous tourist spots.

    [20]:
     
    generation_config = GenerateContentConfig(temperature=1.0)
    ​
    chat = client.chats.create(
        model=MODEL_ID,
        config=GenerateContentConfig(
            system_instruction=[
                "Hello! You are an AI chatbot for a travel web site.",
                "Your mission is to provide helpful queries for travelers.",
                "Remember that before you answer a question, you must check to see if it complies with your mission.",
                "If not, you can say, Sorry I can't answer that question.",
            ]
        ),
    )
    ​
    prompt = "What is the best place for sightseeing in Milan, Italy?"
    ​
    response = chat.send_message(prompt)
    display(Markdown(response.text))

    Milan offers many fantastic sightseeing opportunities!

    For the absolute best and most iconic place for sightseeing in Milan, I would highly recommend Duomo di Milano (Milan Cathedral).

    Here's why:

    • Architectural Marvel: It's one of the largest and most intricate Gothic cathedrals in the world, with stunning spires, statues, and stained-glass windows.
    • Panoramic Views: You can take an elevator or stairs to the Duomo Terraces for breathtaking panoramic views of Milan, including the Galleria Vittorio Emanuele II and, on a clear day, even the Alps.
    • Central Location: It's located in the very heart of the city, making it a perfect starting point for exploring other nearby attractions.

    After visiting the Duomo, you can easily walk to the beautiful Galleria Vittorio Emanuele II (a historic shopping arcade) and then on to the famous opera house, Teatro alla Scala.

    Enjoy your trip to Milan!

    xxxxxxxxxx

    Now let us pretend to be a user asks the chatbot a question that is unrelated to travel.

    [21]:
     
    prompt = "How do I make pizza dough at home?"
    ​
    response = chat.send_message(prompt)
    display(Markdown(response.text))

    Sorry, I can't answer that question. My mission is to provide helpful queries for travelers.

    xxxxxxxxxx

    You can see that this way, a guardrail in the prompt prevented the chatbot from veering off course.

    Turn generative tasks into classification tasks to reduce output variability¶

    Generative tasks lead to higher output variability¶

    The prompt below results in an open-ended response, useful for brainstorming, but response is highly variable.

    [22]:
     
    prompt = "I'm a high school student. Recommend me a programming activity to improve my skills."
    ​
    response = client.models.generate_content(model=MODEL_ID, contents=prompt)
    display(Markdown(response.text))

    That's fantastic! The best way to improve is by building things. Here are a few activity recommendations, ranging in complexity, along with what skills they'll help you develop. I'll assume you're probably using Python, as it's excellent for beginners, but most of these ideas can be adapted to other languages.

    General Advice Before You Start:¶

    1. Choose a Language: If you haven't picked one, Python is highly recommended for its readability and vast resources.
    2. Start Small: Don't try to build the next Facebook on your first project. Break down big ideas into tiny, manageable steps.
    3. Use Version Control (Git): Even for solo projects, learning Git is invaluable. It lets you save different versions of your code, experiment safely, and easily revert mistakes. Start with GitHub or GitLab.
    4. Google is Your Best Friend: When you get stuck, chances are someone else has had the same problem. Learn to search effectively.
    5. Debugging: Learning to find and fix errors (bugs) is a core programming skill. Print statements, using a debugger, and reading error messages are crucial.
    6. Read Others' Code: Look at how other people solve problems. This can give you new ideas and expose you to different coding styles.

    Project Recommendations:¶

    1. Text-Based Adventure Game / Choose Your Own Adventure¶

    • Description: Create a simple game where the user makes choices that dictate the story's progression. "You are in a dark forest. Do you go left or right?"
    • What you'll learn:
      • Conditional Logic (if/elif/else): The core of decision-making.
      • Loops (while): To keep the game running until an end condition is met.
      • Functions: To organize different parts of your story or game states.
      • User Input (input()): Taking choices from the player.
      • String Manipulation: Displaying text, formatting messages.
      • Basic Game Design: Thinking about narrative flow and player experience.
    • How to get started:
      1. Map out a very simple story on paper (e.g., 3-4 rooms/scenes).
      2. Implement the first "room" and its choices.
      3. Add functions for each subsequent room.
      4. Connect them using if/elif/else statements.
    • Bonus Challenges:
      • Add an inventory system (using lists or dictionaries).
      • Introduce "health" or "score" variables.
      • Implement "puzzles" that require specific items or actions.
      • Save and load game progress to a file.

    2. Simple Command-Line Utility (e.g., To-Do List, Password Generator)¶

    • Description: Build a small tool that performs a useful function directly from your computer's terminal.
      • To-Do List: Add tasks, mark them complete, view all tasks, delete tasks.
      • Password Generator: Generate random, strong passwords based on user criteria (length, inclusion of numbers/symbols).
    • What you'll learn (To-Do List example):
      • Data Structures (Lists/Dictionaries): Storing your tasks.
      • File I/O: Saving and loading your tasks to a text file so they persist between sessions.
      • Functions: For adding, viewing, completing, deleting tasks.
      • User Interaction (input(), print()): Creating a menu-driven interface.
      • Error Handling (try/except): What if the user enters invalid input?
    • What you'll learn (Password Generator example):
      • Randomness (random module): Generating random characters.
      • String Manipulation: Combining characters, creating complex strings.
      • Functions: For specific parts of the generation process.
      • Input Validation: Ensuring the user inputs valid numbers for length, etc.
    • How to get started:
      1. Decide on the core functionality (e.g., for To-Do: just add and view).
      2. Implement that core functionality.
      3. Add persistence (saving to a file).
      4. Build out more features incrementally.
    • Bonus Challenges:
      • To-Do List: Add priorities, due dates, categories.
      • Password Generator: Allow exclusion of similar characters (like 'l' and '1'), copy to clipboard functionality (requires external library).

    3. Basic Web Scraper¶

    • Description: Write a program that automatically extracts specific information from a website. This is how price comparison sites or news aggregators work.
    • What you'll learn:
      • HTTP Requests (requests library in Python): How programs communicate with websites.
      • HTML Parsing (BeautifulSoup library in Python): How to navigate the structure of a webpage and extract data.
      • Data Extraction: Identifying patterns and selectors to get the specific text/images you want.
      • Error Handling: What if the website is down or changes its structure?
      • Data Storage: Saving the extracted data to a CSV file or a simple database.
    • How to get started:
      1. Pick a simple website with publicly available data (e.g., a movie review site, a weather site, or even a simple Wikipedia page).
      2. Use your browser's developer tools (right-click -> "Inspect") to examine the HTML structure and find the elements you want to target.
      3. Write code to fetch the page content.
      4. Use BeautifulSoup to find and extract the desired information.
    • Bonus Challenges:
      • Scrape multiple pages.
      • Handle pagination (moving from page 1 to page 2, etc.).
      • Store the data in a more structured format (JSON, CSV).
      • Create a simple analysis of the scraped data (e.g., find the average rating of movies).
      • Important: Always be mindful of a website's robots.txt file and terms of service. Don't overload servers or scrape sensitive data.

    4. Simple Graphical User Interface (GUI) Application¶

    • Description: Move beyond text-only programs and create an application with buttons, text fields, and visual elements. A basic calculator, a unit converter, or a simple drawing app.
    • What you'll learn:
      • GUI Frameworks: Tkinter (built into Python, good for beginners), PyQt, Kivy, or PyGame (for games).
      • Event Handling: Responding to user actions (button clicks, key presses).
      • Widgets: Understanding and using buttons, labels, text entry fields, etc.
      • Layout Management: Arranging your GUI elements neatly.
      • Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) concepts: Many GUI frameworks encourage or require thinking in terms of classes and objects.
    • How to get started (Tkinter):
      1. Follow a basic Tkinter tutorial to create a window and add a button.
      2. Make the button do something simple (e.g., print "Hello!" to the console).
      3. Add an input field and a label.
      4. Build a simple application like a Celsius to Fahrenheit converter.
    • Bonus Challenges:
      • Create a simple game like Tic-Tac-Toe or Snake with a GUI.
      • Integrate one of your previous command-line projects into a GUI.
      • Learn how to package your GUI application so others can run it without installing Python.

    Choose the project that excites you the most! The key is to start coding, make mistakes, and learn from them. Good luck!

    xxxxxxxxxx

    Classification tasks reduces output variability¶

    The prompt below results in a choice and may be useful if you want the output to be easier to control.

    [23]:
     
    prompt = """I'm a high school student. Which of these activities do you suggest and why:
    a) learn Python
    b) learn JavaScript
    c) learn Fortran
    """
    ​
    response = client.models.generate_content(model=MODEL_ID, contents=prompt)
    display(Markdown(response.text))

    That's a fantastic question, and it shows you're thinking strategically about your future! For a high school student, the choice of a first programming language can significantly impact your learning journey and future interests.

    Let's break down each option:

    a) Learn Python¶

    Why you SHOULD consider it:

    1. Beginner-Friendly & Readable: Python's syntax is often described as being close to plain English. This makes it incredibly easy to read and write, reducing frustration for beginners and allowing you to focus on programming concepts rather than cryptic syntax.
    2. Extremely Versatile: Python is used in almost every field imaginable:
      • Web Development: (e.g., Django, Flask) for building websites and web applications.
      • Data Science & Machine Learning/AI: This is where Python shines, with powerful libraries like NumPy, Pandas, Scikit-learn, and TensorFlow. If you're interested in AI, this is your gateway.
      • Automation & Scripting: Automating repetitive tasks on your computer.
      • Scientific Computing: Used heavily in academia and research.
      • Game Development: (e.g., Pygame) for simple games.
      • Desktop Applications: (e.g., PyQt, Kivy).
    3. Huge Community & Resources: Because it's so popular, there are tons of tutorials, online courses, forums, and communities to help you when you get stuck.
    4. Immediate Gratification: You can write small, useful programs very quickly.

    Why you MIGHT pause:

    • Performance: For extremely high-performance, low-level tasks, Python can be slower than compiled languages like C++ or Java (or Fortran). However, for almost everything a beginner will do, this is completely irrelevant.

    Ideal for you if: You want a language that's easy to start with, highly versatile, and opens doors to exciting fields like AI, data science, and web development.

    b) Learn JavaScript¶

    Why you SHOULD consider it:

    1. The Language of the Web: JavaScript is the language that makes websites interactive. If you want to build anything that runs in a web browser (buttons, animations, forms, interactive elements), you need JavaScript.
    2. Immediate Visual Feedback: You can see your code come to life directly in your web browser. This can be incredibly motivating and engaging.
    3. "Full-Stack" Potential: With Node.js, JavaScript can also be used for server-side programming (the "backend" of a website). This means you can build an entire web application (frontend and backend) using just one language.
    4. High Demand: Web development skills are always in high demand in the job market.
    5. Beyond the Browser: It's also used for mobile apps (React Native) and desktop apps (Electron).

    Why you MIGHT pause:

    • Can be a bit quirky: Some of its fundamental concepts can be a little less intuitive for a very first programming language compared to Python, especially its asynchronous nature.
    • Ecosystem Overwhelm: The JavaScript ecosystem (frameworks, libraries, build tools) can seem vast and intimidating to a beginner, though you don't need to learn all of it at once.

    Ideal for you if: You are passionate about building interactive websites, web applications, or anything that visually engages users. You like immediate, visual results.

    c) Learn Fortran¶

    Why you SHOULD consider it:

    1. High Performance Scientific Computing: Fortran (short for FORmula TRANslation) was designed specifically for numerical and scientific computing. It's incredibly efficient for complex calculations, simulations, and large datasets.
    2. Legacy Code & Specific Niche: It's still widely used in fields like meteorology, aerospace engineering, physics, computational fluid dynamics, and supercomputing centers because many critical, highly optimized programs were written in Fortran decades ago and are still maintained.
    3. Teaches Efficiency: If you eventually get into performance optimization and understanding how computers handle numbers at a low level, Fortran is very insightful.

    Why you MIGHT pause:

    • NOT Beginner-Friendly: For a high school student learning their first language, Fortran is generally a poor choice. Its syntax is less intuitive, and it's much harder to get started with basic tasks.
    • Very Niche: Its applications are highly specialized. Unless you are absolutely certain you want to pursue a very specific scientific or engineering career that relies on legacy Fortran code, it won't give you the broad applicability of Python or JavaScript.
    • Less Modern Ecosystem: Fewer modern tutorials, libraries, and communities for general programming tasks compared to Python or JavaScript. You won't be building websites or AI models with it.
    • Less Engaging: Most Fortran programs are command-line based, offering less immediate visual feedback or interactive elements.

    Ideal for you if: You are already deeply committed to a specific scientific or engineering field (e.g., aerospace, quantum physics) and know that Fortran is a dominant language in that very specific niche. For general learning, it's not recommended as a first language.

    My Recommendation for a High School Student:¶

    Start with Python, and then potentially move to JavaScript.

    Here's why:

    1. Python provides the smoothest entry: You'll grasp core programming concepts (variables, loops, functions, data structures) with less struggle because of its clear syntax. This builds confidence and makes learning programming fun.
    2. Broad foundational skills: Python's versatility means you can explore many different areas (data, AI, web backend, scripting) to see what truly interests you.
    3. Then, if you're drawn to web development, learn JavaScript: Once you have a solid grasp of programming fundamentals from Python, picking up JavaScript will be much easier. You'll already understand how to think like a programmer, and you'll then learn the specifics of how JavaScript applies those concepts to the web. This gives you a powerful combination (backend with Python, frontend with JavaScript).

    Fortran, while powerful in its niche, is almost certainly not the right starting point for a high school student unless you have a very specific, advanced scientific/engineering pathway already mapped out and validated by experts in that field. You can always learn it later if your interests genuinely lead you there after building a strong foundation.

    Key takeaway: Focus on learning how to think like a programmer and solve problems first. Python is excellent for that. The specific language syntax is secondary. Good luck!

    xxxxxxxxxx

    Improve response quality by including examples¶

    Another way to improve response quality is to add examples in your prompt. The LLM learns in-context from the examples on how to respond. Typically, one to five examples (shots) are enough to improve the quality of responses. Including too many examples can cause the model to over-fit the data and reduce the quality of responses.

    Similar to classical model training, the quality and distribution of the examples is very important. Pick examples that are representative of the scenarios that you need the model to learn, and keep the distribution of the examples (e.g. number of examples per class in the case of classification) aligned with your actual distribution.

    Zero-shot prompt¶

    Below is an example of zero-shot prompting, where you don't provide any examples to the LLM within the prompt itself.

    [24]:
     
    prompt = """Decide whether a Tweet's sentiment is positive, neutral, or negative.
    ​
    Tweet: I loved the new YouTube video you made!
    Sentiment:
    """
    ​
    response = client.models.generate_content(model=MODEL_ID, contents=prompt)
    display(Markdown(response.text))

    Positive

    xxxxxxxxxx

    One-shot prompt¶

    Below is an example of one-shot prompting, where you provide one example to the LLM within the prompt to give some guidance on what type of response you want.

    [25]:
     
    prompt = """Decide whether a Tweet's sentiment is positive, neutral, or negative.
    ​
    Tweet: I loved the new YouTube video you made!
    Sentiment: positive
    ​
    Tweet: That was awful. Super boring 😠
    Sentiment:
    """
    ​
    response = client.models.generate_content(model=MODEL_ID, contents=prompt)
    display(Markdown(response.text))

    negative

    xxxxxxxxxx

    Few-shot prompt¶

    Below is an example of few-shot prompting, where you provide a few examples to the LLM within the prompt to give some guidance on what type of response you want.

    [26]:
     
    prompt = """Decide whether a Tweet's sentiment is positive, neutral, or negative.
    ​
    Tweet: I loved the new YouTube video you made!
    Sentiment: positive
    ​
    Tweet: That was awful. Super boring 😠
    Sentiment: negative
    ​
    Tweet: Something surprised me about this video - it was actually original. It was not the same old recycled stuff that I always see. Watch it - you will not regret it.
    Sentiment:
    """
    ​
    response = client.models.generate_content(model=MODEL_ID, contents=prompt)
    display(Markdown(response.text))

    positive

    Choosing between zero-shot, one-shot, few-shot prompting methods¶

    xxxxxxxxxx

    Which prompt technique to use will solely depends on your goal. The zero-shot prompts are more open-ended and can give you creative answers, while one-shot and few-shot prompts teach the model how to behave so you can get more predictable answers that are consistent with the examples provided.
